Butane Blending is a batch-type process based on seasonal regulatory Reid Vapor Pressure (RVP) adjustments. Butane is received by truck (transports), stored on-site (a second vessel is being added to the process and is included in this RMP), and piped directly to injection points feeding the dock and off-site locations. Process safety controls include "Smart-Hoses", low emission couplers, emergency shutoff valves (ESVs) throughout (manual, automated and thermally actuated), vessel PRVs, excess flow valves, hydrostatic pressure relief, and process area hydrocarbon detectors along with on-site fire water monitors. Access to the Kenova LP Terminal and butane offload/storage area is restricted to authorized employees, management personnel and authorized contractors/visitors.

B. GENERAL ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM AND CHEMICAL-SPECIFIC PREVENTION MEASURES

The Kenova LP Terminal accidental release prevention programs and emergency planning/response programs help effectively manage the hazards posed by butane to the Terminal employees, surrounding public, and environment. The covered process is regulated by the EPA RMP regulation 40 CFR Part 68, as well as the OSHA Process Safety Management standard 29 CFR 1910.119. The following accident prevention program elements are in place at the Kenova LP Terminal:

1) Employee Participation;
2) Process Safety Information;
3) Process Hazard Analysis (PHA);
4) Standard Operating Procedures;
5) Training;
6) Contractors;
7) Pre-startup Safety Review;
8) Mechanical Integrity with Inspection, Testing and Preventive Maintenance;
9) Hazardous/Hot Work Permits;
