These fourteen (14) individual elements work together to prevent/detect accidental chemical releases and minimize/mitigate their impacts if an incident were to occur. MPLX and its employees are committed to the standards required by these management programs. In addition to the above elements, MPLX also has specific prevention measures that are employed as part of the Terminal's operating procedures along with engineering and administrative controls to help identify/contain/control a release and reduce potential adverse impacts. These are briefly summarized as follows:

General Risk Reduction and Safety Measures

-Engineering and construction in accordance with recognized industry and company standards;
-Equipment properly designed with protection from overpressure (pressure safety relief valves, etc.);
-Updated technical drawings, Piping & Instrumentation Diagrams and Process/Block Flow Diagrams;
-Operating systems monitored and controlled by trained Operators;
-Redundant control/safety systems;
-Manual and automated shutdown devices for critical systems;
-Scheduled inspection and testing of safety devices and critical components;
-Limited/secured facility access;
-Regular safety meetings and safety awareness programs;
-Routinely scheduled safety inspections and audits; and
-Frequent unit surveillance by operators.

General Release Mitigation

-Process shutoffs to limit release quantity (also actuated via a fusible
elements in the event of a fire);
-Excess Flow Valves;
-Hydrocarbon Detectors with automatic process shutdown functions; 
-Strategically located valves to isolate leaks; and
-"Smart-Hoses" with design break-away and self-closing valves on each end.

General Emergency Response

